04476nam a22005295i 9780774836296DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748362967 a10.59962/97807748362962doi  a(DE-B1597)661853  a(OCoLC)992558700  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aPOL0690002bisacsh04a958.104/7qOCoLC223/eng/202311201 aBoucher, Jean-Christophe, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Politics of War :bCanada’s Afghanistan Mission, 2001–14 /cJean-Christophe Boucher, Kim Richard Nossal. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (300 p.) :b9 graphs, 2 maps, 6 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAbbreviations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Domestic Politics of Canada’s Afghanistan Mission -- tThe Away Game: Canadians in Afghanistan -- tThe War That Wasn’t: Framing the Mission -- tHome Pitch: Selling Afghanistan to Canadians -- tParliament’s Role: Laundering the Mission -- tDon’t Mention the War: Electoral Politics and Bipartisanship -- tDetainee Games: The Politics of Distraction -- tDid Minority Government Matter? A Counterfactual Analysis -- tAn Unpopular Mission: Public Opinion and Afghanistan -- tThe Politics of Casualties: Evaluating the “Trenton Effect” -- tFailure to Launch: Public Mobilization and the War in Afghanistan -- tConclusion: Though Poppies Grow -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen the Canadian government committed forces to join the military mission in Afghanistan following the terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001, little did it foresee that this decision would involve Canada in a war-riven country for over a decade. The Politics of War explores how, as the mission became increasingly unpopular, Canadian politicians across the political spectrum began to use it to score points against their opponents. This was “politics” with a vengeance. Through historical analysis of the public record and interviews with officials, Jean-Christophe Boucher and Kim Richard Nossal show how the Canadian government sought to frame the engagement in Afghanistan as a “mission” rather than what it was – a war. They examine the efforts of successive governments to convince Canadians of the rightness of Canada’s engagement, the parliamentary politics that resulted from the increasing politicization of the mission, and the impact of public opinion on Canada’s involvement. This contribution to the field of Canadian foreign policy demonstrates how much of Canada’s war in Afghanistan was shaped by the vagaries of domestic politics and political gamesmanship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Military Policy.2bisacsh1 aNossal, Kim Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311141793640uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077483629640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774836296423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774836296/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-141793-6  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles